"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-what-to-watch-paris-olympics-august-4-noah-lyles-goes-for-first-gold\", \"text\": \"Day 9 of the Olympics is here, and it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s another big one. Here\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s my daily guide to help you know what events to watch. It should do the trick whether you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re planning to spend a full Sunday in front of the TV or just picking and choosing spots.  You can also subscribe toSports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daily Rings, my daily podcast where Dan Gartland and I are recapping the Games every night. New episodes have been published every night before NBC\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s prime-time coverage is even over.  Here\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be watching Sunday, August 4.  This is not a comprehensive list;visit Olympics.comfor a full schedule. All events will stream live on Peacock. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll also be tweeting out a schedule of medal events, Team USA games and other favorites each day.  My Day 9 Olympics viewing guide! Hopefully this time with no typos, but no promises. Fun Sunday on tap#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/5G2UxDMYRQ  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s time for the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 100 meters. Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Noah Lyles is the reigning world champ, though Jamaica\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Kishane Thompson is the betting favorite. No American man has won this event since 2004\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094of course a guy by the name of Usain Bolt was in the way for a while.  The race starts at 3:50 p.m. ET, and don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t tune in late because it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be over in less than 10 seconds. The other gold medals that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be awarded during the afternoon track and field session are the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hammer throw and women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s high jump.  Sunday is the final round of the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s golf tournament, and we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve got a great leaderboard. American Xander Schauffele is tied with Spain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s John Rahm for first place at 14-under. Then Great Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Tommy Fleetwood is one shot behind. They\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll make up the final group. American and world No. 1 Scottie Scheffler is in a group four shots off the lead.  Golf begins at 3 a.m. ET, but the leaders won\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t go off until 6:39 a.m. and should hit the back nine in the nine o\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099clock hour.  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the last day of tennis, and we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve got three Olympic matches left. We\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll see bronze and gold matches to wrap up women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s doubles, with a dream matchup in between them.\\u00c2  The men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s singles tournament has come down to Novak Djokovic vs. Carlos Alcaraz, the top two seeds in the tournament. Djokovic has an all-time record 24 Grand Slam singles titles; he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s won everything there is to win except an Olympic gold. Alcaraz has won four Grand Slams and is viewed as the next man up.  Tennis starts at 6 a.m. and they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be the second match on the court, followed by the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s doubles gold match.  The final day of indoor swimming (we still have marathon swimming to come) has four medal events beginning at 12:30 p.m. ET: the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 50-meter freestyle, the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 1500-meter free, and both the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s and women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 4X100 medley relays.  In cycling, the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s road race was a fun watch Saturday morning and the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s event goes off Sunday at 8 a.m. ET.  Beach volleyball has reached the round of 16. Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Sara Hughes and Kelly Cheng will face a team from Italy at 4 p.m. ET. (The Nuss/Kloth team will have its round of 16 game the next day.)  If you read my post yesterday, you know how excited I am forkayak cross: Heats continue on Sunday, now with four kayaks in the water at once instead of three. Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Evy Leibfarth will be in the fifth heat of the session at 10:45 a.m. ET.  Team USA archer Brady Ellison already won his fourth Olympic medal this week in the mixed team event. He has an early-morning quarterfinal in the individual competition, hoping to advance all the way to the medal matches just after 8:30 a.m. ET.  The U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s basketball team continues group play against Germany at 11:15 a.m. ET.  The men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s singles table tennis medals will be awarded Sunday morning. Defending Olympic silver medalist Fan Zhendong will go for gold andfan-favorite 17-year-old Felix LeBrunwill compete for bronze. Action starts at 7:30 a.m. ET.  Finally, listeners of my podcast know I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be glued to the Croatia vs. Spain men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s handball game at 3 p.m. ET. Only one will advance out of group play.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Mitch Goldich is a senior editor for Sports Illustrated, mostly focused on the NFL. He has also covered the Olympics extensively and written on a variety of sports since joining SI in 2014. His work has been published by The New York Times, Baseball Prospectus and Food & Wine, among other outlets. Goldich has a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from Lehigh University and a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from the Medill School at Northwestern University. He is a Philly native, now living in Boston, and he invented and popularized the octopus, when the same player scores a touchdown and the ensuing two-point conversion.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"